<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: WORKERS MARCH TO DOOR OF EX-EMPLOYER, 
DEMAND PAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four undocumented workers who said they were cheated out of $1,600 in back pay 
by their former employer marched down a quiet suburban street to the man's 
rented hilltop home in Granada Hills Thursday, demanding payment. 
</P>
<P>
The men were joined by about 20 other immigrant workers in a demonstration 
outside Fernando Esquivia's two-story home on Elnora Place. 
</P>
<P>
Many carried placards with the messages, "No More Abuse for Undocumented 
Workers," and "We Are Not Animals. We are Human Beings. Exercise Social Justice 
for Undocumented Workers." 
</P>
<P>
The men, accompanied by reporters and representatives from the Coalition for 
Humane Immigrant Rights in Los Angeles, knocked on the door of the home, but no 
one answered. 
</P>
<P>
Esquivia, in a later interview, said that he did not owe the men any money. 
</P>
<P>
"They're liars," Esquivia said. "If I owed them money, I would give it to them. 
I'm not guilty." 
</P>
</TEXT>
