P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
LLOYDS POSTS $1.2-BILLION LOSS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lloyds Bank of Britain posted a pretax loss of $1.2 billion today after a huge 
provision against loans to developing countries undermined hefty profits made 
in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
"The fact that our 1989 figures show a substantial loss arises from the large 
provision we have made for Third World debt," Lloyds Chairman Sir Jeremy Morse 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
"As a result we are fully covered for that part of the debt which is doubtful, 
and the worst of this long-running problem should be behind us," he added. 
</P>
<P>
Lloyds Bank PLC became the third of the top four British commercial banks to 
see shrunken profits after making a provision of $2.9 billion to cover the debt 
of less developed countries, amounting to 70% of total exposure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
