</P>
<P>
IRS CITES FOXX EXPENDITURES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Comedian Redd Foxx was paid $500,000 for his role in the movie "Harlem Nights" 
and spent $373,000 of it on "wine, women, song and gambling," the Internal 
Revenue Service says. 
</P>
<P>
Such expenditures make it unlikely that the IRS can reach agreement with Foxx 
on his tax troubles, IRS attorney Rollin Thorley told a federal bankruptcy 
judge Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Foxx, who gained fame playing a junk dealer on the TV show "Sanford and Son" 
and who now performs at a Las Vegas resort, filed for protection from creditors 
under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy law in 1983. He owes the IRS more than 
$900,000 in taxes, penalties and interest. 
</P>
<P>
The earnings on the recent movie were revealed as Foxx appeared in court to try 
to block a public auction of more than 400 items of personal property seized in 
an IRS raid in November. 
</P>
<P>
The items, including his Las Vegas home, several cars and jewelry, were to be 
sold last month. The sale was delayed while a federal judge tried to decide 
whether the IRS or the bankruptcy court had first claim on the property. 
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy Judge Clive Jones ordered the property seized by the IRS to be held 
"in limbo" for 60 days while lawyers try to reach agreement. 
</P>
<P>
Foxx failed in bids to block the IRS from seizing his paychecks for back taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
